# Reference only -- NOT loaded automatically by anything. Every
# REPLACE_ME_* placeholder repeated across the per-service files in this
# directory means the same thing every time it appears:
#
#   REPLACE_ME_DB_HOST        host of the production Postgres instance
#   REPLACE_ME_DB_PASSWORD    the `platform` role's real password (not "platform"
#                             and not the same password used in staging)
#   REPLACE_ME_KAFKA_BROKERS  e.g. "kafka-1.prod.internal:9092,kafka-2.prod.internal:9092"
#   REPLACE_ME_REDIS_HOST     e.g. "redis.prod.internal:6379"
#   REPLACE_ME_CLICKHOUSE_URL e.g. "https://clickhouse.prod.internal:8123"
#   REPLACE_ME_JWT_SECRET     a real random secret, DIFFERENT from staging's --
#                             must be IDENTICAL between auth-service.env.example
#                             and api-gateway.env.example (auth-service signs
#                             tokens, api-gateway verifies them)
#   REPLACE_ME_DOMAIN         the production domain this platform is deployed under
#
# Internal service-to-service URLs below use the placeholder scheme
# "http://<service>.prod.internal:<port>" -- replace with whatever real
# internal DNS/service-discovery scheme production actually uses (K8s Service
# DNS, a service mesh, etc.) once that infrastructure exists. Production
# secrets should come from a real secrets manager (not a plain file on disk)
# once one is in place -- these .env.example files are a starting point, not
# the final word on how production secrets get delivered.
